<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
	xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
	xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd">

<bean id="payment" class="com.rays.autowire.byname.Payment">
	<property name="balance" value="500"></property>
</bean>

<bean id="inventory" class="com.rays.autowire.byname.Inventory">
	<property name="stock" value="10"></property>
</bean>

<bean id="order" class="com.rays.autowire.byname.Order1" autowire="byName"></bean>
	
</beans>
<!-- Dependency Injection using autowire-byname -->
<!-- 
When you use autowire="byName", Spring injects a dependency based on the property name matching a bean name in the Spring container.

So the rule is simple ðŸ‘‡
ðŸ‘‰ Property name = Bean ID

How it works (important idea)

Spring looks at:

The setter method / field name in your class

Tries to find a bean with the same name

If found â†’ injects it

If not found â†’ dependency remains null (no error)
 -->